  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from criminal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or organized crime) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nMoney laundering is criminalized under various national and international laws. For example:\n\n1. **United States**: The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** make it illegal to engage in money laundering activities. The **Patriot Act** also expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations.\n\n2. **European Union**: The EU has implemented several directives, such as the **Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD)**, to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n3. **International Standards**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental body, sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Countries that are members of the FATF are expected to implement these standards into their domestic laws.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment, depending on the jurisdiction and the severity of the offense. Governments and financial institutions are required to implement measures to detect and prevent money laundering, such as customer due diligence, reporting suspicious activities, and maintaining records of financial transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity and is subject to strict legal prohibitions and enforcement measures worldwide.",
